Original caption:

It’s the first time in history that we’ve shot a Tasty Tuesday on an actual Tuesday! Today has confirmed that it’s just way too much work to save for one day, so I will continue to do it a few days in advance! Of course, the day that I have to get it all done is the day that we have our longest video ever at 10 minutes. I have been trying to keep them shorter, but with Babe’s growing kitchen skills comes more complicated recipes - so it’s understandable that the videos will be longer! Hope y’all don’t mind a little extra Chef Babe in your day!

Today, we made a minestrone soup recipe from @vitamix. One of the reasons I splurged on this blender was it’s capability to make soup (it heats it!) without a stovetop. How easy and awesome! I am sad that the chilly weather has arrived, but soup and warm fall meals are definitely a silver lining. The soup came out nice, but Babe was totally just being nice when she said she liked it. Hahaha! I plan on sprucing it up for dinner tonight with some cooked pasta and more spices and hopefully it will win her over.

I love this video because it demonstrates the wide array of skills a toddler can work on while helping you in the kitchen! She hit on math (fractions, counting, measuring), fine motor skills (peeling, handling tools), coordination (bimanual movements, hand eye) strength and gross motor movements (pouring, lifting the blender), and so many more like: attention, following multi-step directions, sequencing, language development, and so on!

Involving your child in cooking and baking is really a gold mine for physical and cognitive development. Plus, it’s FUN and it’s an excellent way to bond with each other! An added bonus is that your child might be more likely to try food that they’ve helped to prepare!

What’s your favorite part about cooking with your kiddo? 👩🏼‍🍳

Since I’m taking a semi-break from creating new content for the rest of August, here’s a vintage Tasty Tuesday! This was about a month and a half before Babe turned two. You can see how I made baking more appropriate for her skill level then. Everything was pre measured and put into little bowls. I also completed some tasks and let her finish them instead of expecting she’d do everything herself. It’s so fun looking back at these videos and seeing all that she’s learned and how she loves taking on new tasks as her skills increase.

Original caption (feb 2020)

This week on Tasty Tuesday, we made Valentine’s Day inspired butter cookies! They were easy to whip together with only a few ingredients and the best part was that Babe got to try the hand mixer - I think it’s pretty obvious that she absolutely loved it.

This recipe called for pouring, mixing, sprinkling, flattening, and transferring! These tasks require concentration, precision, fine motor and gross motor control, visual motor control, strength, problem solving, and following one step and multi-step directions. Baking is such a fun way to exercise little bodies and minds while also boosting their self confidence!

Baking always makes a mess - I view these messes as more opportunities to involve Babe. She really enjoys putting away ingredients, wiping up counters, and doing the dishes. Cleaning up is not only a way to work on more skills, but it’s a way to teach respect of the environment. It’s important to us that we are constantly modeling keeping our home tidy. Babe picks up on it and it shows through the way she keeps her own spaces neat and tidy!

Have you teamed up with your little one in the kitchen this week? Did you make something tasty? I’d love to see!

Kitchen tools from @montikids, discount code BABE!
Apron: @whitebirchgrove

This week, we kept it simple with a box of delicious corn bread. All the fun with less stress & mess! Babe got to crack eggs (she insisted she try it on the bowl instead of the counter), measure ingredients, grease pans, and more!

Babe the yolk-slayer is back with her chop chop chopping of yolks, and she  even talks about her strategies and tells me how much she loves breaking those darn yolks every time we use eggs! 🥚 

I think my favorite part of this weeks video is her confused ending of Twinkle Twinkle, Little Star. Or maybe her use of the phrase “bad boy” which is always hilarious. I use that phrase often and it’s definitely rubbing off on her!

Hope you enjoy this weeks video! Don’t forget to let us know your favorite part!

We made the most delicious blueberry muffins using the berries we picked last week! They were “dee-licious” in Babes words!

This was a fun one - especially the part when she’s trying to fill the measuring cup with blueberries! Babe loves cracking eggs, measuring liquids, and using the masher, so she had a really great time with these. I’ll link the recipe in my stories - we highly recommend them warm out of the oven and then grilled with butter for breakfast. 💙

I’m keeping this write up short because the captioning software and my phone storage have stressed me out to the max today. I keep saying I’m going to deliver shorter videos, but here I am with another 12 minuter. 🤪

Hope you enjoy - don’t forget to tell us your favorite part below!

This is probably my favorite recent video - she was goofy and adorable and it’s impossible me to choose a favorite part! Maybe giCantic or “my voice sounds like piglet actually.” We hadn’t been talking about Winnie the Pooh at all, but she did mention earlier that her voice “sounded weak” so I guess she finally came to the realization that she reminded herself of piglet. 😆

Anyway - hope you all enjoy this very fun and cute video! Don’t forget to tell us your favorite part!

Babe made a smoothie - our favorite smoothie that we make a lot with the new addition of kiwi! Babe loves making smoothies because she can basically do it on her own and she loves taking charge of the process!

Smoothies are a fun way to get in practical life practice (cutting, peeling, transferring etc) without a huge production. It’s straight forward, doesn’t make a huge mess, and a delicious treat!

I love doing smoothies for Tasty Tuesday every once in awhile because it’s fun to look back on older ones and see how her techniques and skills have developed over time.

Do you like making smoothies?

This week, we conquered cut out cookies from dough to decorating! We were gifted a cookie making kit from @foodstirs (but this is not sponsored content!) and we finally got around to making them! I knew I wanted to make them for a Tasty Tuesday video, but I also knew it was going to take way longer than normal and make my editing job more complicated. I was right - the raw footage for this video was over an hour (it’s usually 20 minutes) and I had such a hard time cutting it down to a decently sized video because there were so many components to the cookies. So we hope you enjoy this almost 12 minute video!

Anyway - we had so much FUN making these and would make them again in a heartbeat, just never again for Tasty Tuesday. Haha! The cookies were delicious and everyone we shared them with agreed!

This was an extra fun project for Babe because she got to do all of her favorite baking tasks plus the ones she only gets to do on occasion, like rolling out dough, cutting the cookies, and decorating them! She also loved when we rolled up our sleeves and mixed the dough with our hands.

In case you’re new here, Yam is Babe’s imaginary dog. He and Babe do a lot together and they recently adopted a new puppy. Babe reminisced about the time the three of them made cookies like these in the video. 🤣

Hope you enjoy the video - don’t forget to let us know your favorite part!

- Shes standing on her tower from @sprout_kids, code BABE10
- Kid friendly knife and other tools can be found in my Amazon, link in bio.

This week, we made some muffins! I had gifted a box of @thepeachtruck peaches to my in-laws but they ended up being delivered while they were away on a last minute vacation. I was happy to inherit them and Babe suggested we make some peach ginger muffins, since we love getting them at one of our favorite bakeries.  I had other plans for Tasty Tuesday, but they could wait, especially since we had a ton of delicious ripe peaches that were begging to be used!

The recipe I found (these muffins were made from scratch - aren’t you proud, Donna?!) called for turning the peaches into compote which was a fun extra component for Babe. She has used the stovetop a handful of times and was happy to do it again. She also got to use the immersion blender which was a first!

Speaking of Donna and boxed baked good haters - I want to talk about the fact that any exposure in the kitchen is great for your kid. Boxed or not, they are still learning a ton, gaining new skills, practicing old ones, and being exposed to so much that they may not be elsewhere. I would never want to give y’all the impression that I only bake from scratch because that would be a huge lie! Most of you guys know my kitchen skills are lacking, but I don’t let that stop me from teaching Babe! Boxed mixes are great - taking a bunch of ingredients and steps off of the to-do list makes baking with a toddler or young child much more approachable. Do what you want and don’t let anyone make you feel bad about it. The fact that you are in the kitchen with your kid is what matters… not if your muffins came from a box or not! Even if your end product isn’t great, it’s the process that matters most!

Anyway, we had a great time making these. Babe didn’t get to measure much out because we were limited on time, but we made up for it with lots of scooping (her hands got a great workout!) and using the stove and immersion blender.

What was your favorite part?!

I cannot believe that this is our 81st video in this series. Phew! This week, we made scrumptious mini muffins this week using @simplemills mix. We added some extra deliciousness in the form of chocolate chips and walnuts and the end result was amazing. I inhaled about 5 while captioning this video!

Babe loved this recipe because of the THREE eggs she got to crack! She’s getting her egg crackin groove back - for awhile there she was slamming them on the counter and then crushing them between her hands. 🤣 I knew a little more practice was all she needed!

The mini cookie scooper is quickly becoming her favorite kitchen tool. I LOVED watching her scoop the muffins. It takes so much precision and concentration and she did such a fabulous job. I modeled it for her by doing the first two and then let her take over. It took awwhiiilleeee for her to do them, but she was really enjoying herself and I accepted long ago that baking with kids takes much, much longer. When she needs a break with something (like scooping or mixing) she knows that I’m standing by and ready to take a turn! It gives her a minute to regroup and then jump back in!

Babe is so funny with always making sure I use oven mitts. She has such a cautious personality - I can 100% see her as a hall monitor or crossing guard one day 🤣. I finally explained to her that I don’t need oven mitts to put a cool pan into the oven - just when I’m taking something out. We will see if she remembers that lesson next time we bake together. 🥰

I think my favorite part of this video is her new HA HAs. She said it a few times today and it made me laugh when I watched the full video. We also enjoyed bringing our treats to the beach and sharing with friends. What was your favorite part this week?

Babe and I made some really delicious almond flour chocolate chip cranberry cookies! To keep it simple, we used a boxed mix. Things are much easier for me when there are less ingredients and less steps. No shame in my not from scratch game!

I cannot even begin to choose my favorite part. Babe was on a roll this week and her fun personality really shined through. If you don’t know, Yam is her faithful imaginary dog that she acquired over a year ago. They are best pals. He’s a tiny golden retriever that fits in the palm of her hand and is always at the groomer because his hair grows over his eyes and he has a hard time seeing. I love listening to her stories about Yam and I also love how distracted she got when she saw the picture of herself in the chef hat on the fridge. (It’s a grocery list pad from @pinholepress, actually!) “I’m happy, you’re excited” made ME so happy. I love listening to her identifying her emotions like that! She’s been loving her All About Feelings book lately. 🥰

This was a great recipe for her because she loves a good egg crack (that was SO nice of that egg to crack itself, wasn’t it?!) and of course she always enjoys using the mini scoop - it is easy for her little hands to work and it makes the perfectly sized cookies!

What was your favorite part?! Hope you enjoy this weeks video!

DIY GAME: POM POM SOUP

This is a cute little game using materials you might already have at home. All you need is a bowl, some pom poms, and a spoon! Create “recipes” on a card and then let them cook away.

This game combines Babe’s favorite activity of cooking with number recognition, color recognition, and counting. You can make this easier by drawing out the number of pom poms instead of using the actual number written out. (🔴🔴🔴 instead of “3 red”) Make it harder by using bigger numbers, more ingredients, or add some tongs!

Babe seriously loves this little game and we hope your kids do, too! 💛

Babe is almost 3.5 and is sitting at her little weaning table from @sprout_kids - code BABE10!

THROWBACK THURSDAY
 
Babe must have been around 20/21 months old here but this is a fun and easy to setup activity that can be graded to many skill levels!

BALL TOSS

Tis the season of big boxes arriving at our houses - this bad boy showed up yesterday with Dad’s big present inside and I knew I had to take advantage of it! Babe has been super into throwing her big soft ball when playing catch with me so I thought I’d mix it up a little bit and make an activity with her smaller soft  balls. I put a piece of painter’s tape on the floor as guide for her to stand on.

This fun ball toss activity is a good one for visual motor skills, fine and gross motor skills, balance, coordination, and concentration! It challenges the ability to follow multi step directions - pick up a ball, make sure you’re standing in the right place, and toss it! You can grade this activity to make it more challenging by moving the tape further from the box and/or making the hole on the box smaller!

Do you already have the supplies to whip this easy activity together?

node.text:
3 POPSICLE STICK PUZZLES

We’re almost back from our little hiatus, we thought we’d pop in to  show you 3 very simple puzzle setups using only popsicle sticks, markers, and stickers! Just draw a design and mix them up or stick some stickers on and use an exacto knife to cut them apart.

Babe enjoyed these puzzles a lot. It helped work on her motor skills, problem solving, and observational skills! Do you think your child would enjoy them?

- Babe is almost 3.5!
- She’s sitting at her weaning table from @sprout_kids (discount code BABE10)

THROWBACK: 19 MONTHS

DIY COLOR FELT WHEEL!

Babe’s been super into colors lately, so I’ve been giving her a lot of color matching activities. This was a super simple one to make, just cut out a circle of felt and then some wedges and use felt glue to put them all together! For the pieces, you can use anything that will fit in the wedges you make! I used yogurt/applesauce tops, rings from another toy, and blocks!

This will be going onto the shelf in her room so she can do it whenever. I switched out the 8 cube shelf for a 4 cube shelf in her room yesterday. I did this for 2 reasons: I will be getting her a twin bed soon so we need the space, and now that she’s sleeping in her bed at night I want to keep the amount and types of activities in her room to just a few low stimulating ones.

Think your little one would like this activity? Easy, cheap, and fun - my favorite combo!

Original caption:

It’s the first time in history that we’ve shot a Tasty Tuesday on an actual Tuesday! Today has confirmed that it’s just way too much work to save for one day, so I will continue to do it a few days in advance! Of course, the day that I have to get it all done is the day that we have our longest video ever at 10 minutes. I have been trying to keep them shorter, but with Babe’s growing kitchen skills comes more complicated recipes - so it’s understandable that the videos will be longer! Hope y’all don’t mind a little extra Chef Babe in your day!

Today, we made a minestrone soup recipe from @vitamix. One of the reasons I splurged on this blender was it’s capability to make soup (it heats it!) without a stovetop. How easy and awesome! I am sad that the chilly weather has arrived, but soup and warm fall meals are definitely a silver lining. The soup came out nice, but Babe was totally just being nice when she said she liked it. Hahaha! I plan on sprucing it up for dinner tonight with some cooked pasta and more spices and hopefully it will win her over.

I love this video because it demonstrates the wide array of skills a toddler can work on while helping you in the kitchen! She hit on math (fractions, counting, measuring), fine motor skills (peeling, handling tools), coordination (bimanual movements, hand eye) strength and gross motor movements (pouring, lifting the blender), and so many more like: attention, following multi-step directions, sequencing, language development, and so on!

Involving your child in cooking and baking is really a gold mine for physical and cognitive development. Plus, it’s FUN and it’s an excellent way to bond with each other! An added bonus is that your child might be more likely to try food that they’ve helped to prepare!

What’s your favorite part about cooking with your kiddo? 👩🏼‍🍳

- Babe is 2.5 years old.
- She is standing on her toddler tower from @sprout_kids. (Discount code BABE10)
- Her perfectly sized apron is from @montikids level 7. (Discount code BABE)

(Watch in full screen for all captions)

Two things toddlers love: snacks and independence! Here are some easy to implement ways to give your child some independence when it comes to snack time.

1. Cut bananas up into slices and let them peel them before eating.
2. Give them some bread or toast, some kind of spread (avocado, hummus, etc) and a small spreader so they can “make” their own snack.
3. Give them the chance to scoop their crunchy snacks into a bowl!
4. Give them a small cup and pitcher to pour their own water. Just remember to only put as much water as you’re willing to clean up! 😜

Remember: messes are a part of learning! Invite your child to help clean up their spills - they’re just another opportunity for growing independence.

What are your favorite ways to include your child in snack prep?

Babe was around 15 months old in these videos.
Small kitchen tools can be found in my Amazon - link in bio!

THROWBACK: 17 MONTHS

Fine motor animal rescue!

Here is another fun and cheap DIY fine motor activity. All you need are little model animals (we love @safariltd, discount code in my bio), painters tape, and a pan! Tape those bad boys down and show your babe how to peel off the tape to set the animal free! I graded this activity to Babe's skill level by leaving the edges of the tape up so she would have something to grab. This activity helps fine motor development, finger strength, grasp development and even language development! You can add a matching component (2 of each animal so they have to rescue them together 🦍🦍) to kick it up a notch.
